Abstract:

The Topic will be regarding PwnTools; a python library designed to help CTF players and exploit developers alike.
The goal of this presentation will be to introduce people to the library, and talk to some of the more interesting modules, and provide examples of how to use the modules.

Covers:
- What is PwnTools
- How to install pwntools
- Several modules covered such as log, ui, tubes, elf, core, rop, dynelf, shellcraft
- Several code examples
- Fuzzing using the Core File to generate an exploit automatically
Bring it all together to make a network based ROP exploit uses a memory leak to defeat ASLR/DEP.

This should go without saying, but please respect their space. We ask that you do not touch their displays, work areas, etc. without permission. Please ask on staff rep for tour.

Looking forward to seeing you all.

Whether adopting scaling out of the gate or taking your organizational change to the next level, there are key concepts that should stay at the forefront of your scaling decision to increase your chances of success: agility, design, and quality. In this session, we will discuss:

- Methods for maintaining responsiveness to changing priorities and needs at the team and organizational level
- How to incorporate good empathetic design techniques into scaling

results.description:
Sivamuthu Kumar.K.A will present "Boost your Bot's IQ - How to turn dumb bot into smart bot..."

Intelligent bots respond as if they can see the world as people see it. They discover information and extract knowledge from different sources to provide useful answers, and, best of all, they learn as they acquire more experience to continuously improve their capabilities

The talk is about how to add intelligence to the bot using Language Understanding Service (LUIS), Microsoft Bot Framework - NodeJS and Azure Services.

In this session, we are going to discuss

- Introduction - Components of the chat-bot framework
Bot Builder SDK for NodeJS - Closer look on the Microsoft's Bot Builder SDK for NodeJS by walking through Dialogs, Actions and State Data management
- Designing conversational flow - Managing conversation flow is an essential task in building bots. How a bot is able to perform core tasks elegantly and handle interruptions gracefully.
- Add Intelligence to Bot - How to train LUIS models and add intelligence to Bot
- Demo - Chatbot that demonstrates the conversational flow and LUIS Language processing.

This event is sponsored by Interactive Resources - http://irtalent.com.

results.description:
Scaling Agile @ Availity
A year ago, Availity‚Äôs executive leaders asked how our teams can be better aligned with the overall strategy of Availity. Sarah Andres (Enterprise Solutions Architect) and Erwin Alberto (Enterprise Solutions Architect) were tasked with answering this question. Sarah and Erwin quickly realized that lack of alignment was primarily due to how Availity planned as an organization. Although teams planned often, they did so in a very localized way. Since Availity has 30+ teams (product teams and shared enterprise teams) planning in their own silos, it was very difficult to achieve the kind of alignment our leaders were asking for. In order to address this issue, Sarah and Erwin introduced the idea of scaling agile where our teams can be in one ‚ÄúBig Room‚Äù planning all at the same time. Our leaders bought into the idea. In November 2017, we launched our first scaled agile event in Availity and it was a huge success. We just finished our second one this past April and are getting ready to do our third in July.

We would like to share with you thier experience in installing and implementing this scaled agile framework in Availity.

- 5:30pm - Refreshments and Networking
- 6pm - Presentation
results.name: Scaling Agile @ Availity

results.description:
Groovy is a scripting language for the JVM. It extends Java in several useful ways. In this presentation, we will learn how to write Groovy scripts such that...
* They run just like any executable file (using hash-bang)
* Fetch Maven packages on the fly and use the jar files therein
* Use complex command line options (with CliBuilder)
* Use JSoup to fetch web pages
* Use JSoup to run jQuery-like DOM queries to scrape them for information
* Connect to a database using its JDBC driver in Groovy
* And run various SQL queries against the JDBC database to save the scraped information

Hopefully this serves as an easy but useful introduction to Groovy and JSoup. The source-code for this presentation will be available at
https://bitbucket.org/spinspire/

About Jitesh Doshi:
Jitesh Doshi is a software entrepreneur who love business, technology and business of technology. He has been coding with Java since 1996, and has built several large, complex, high-performance systems for companies like Nike, GM, IRS and Florida Blue. Through his company, SpinSpire, he loves to mentor new developers and help turn them into "super-developers" while building insanely great software for SpinSpire's clients.
results.name: Web Scraping with Groovy
